Explain loops:

Loops. Perhaps the loopiest programming concept I have come across so far (haha), 
these are programming functions that make an action repeat itself. They are highly 
customizable, so a programmer could make a loop repeat a set number of times, or 
create an expression that has to be true in order for the loop to execute. Or have
 the loop repeat a certain number of times depending on a number the user inputs. 
 Think of how someone may need to repeat an action in the real world a certain number
of times, such as sweeping the floor ___ number of times in order to clean up a 
mess. Programming loops are a digitized version of this repetition, and just like
how different messes require different amounts of sweeping, different programming
tasks may require a statement to repeat a certain number of times. They can be 
dangerous though, because like with a broom, if you use it recklessly, it might 
break, as will the code of a programmer who uses an incorrect loop. All sorts of
chaos could arise, from the programming getting stuck when a loop doesn't repeat enough,
 or to a program spiraling out of control if an infinite loop is incorrectly used.